body:
Hi there!

It seems that Verilator simulates wrongly this small design.

OS:
```
Ubuntu 24.04.2 LTS
```
Verilator version:
```
Verilator 5.033 devel rev v5.032-42-g0507fb465
```
Verilator command:
```
verilator --trace --trace-underscore --cc --exe --build -Wall -Wno-WIDTHTRUNC -Wno-CASEOVERLAP -Wno-UNUSEDSIGNAL -Iobj_dir -Idv -build-jobs 8 top.v dv/toplevel.cc
```

The verilog code is generated but the issue is easy to follow.

`_01_` is 1 as expected, but the assignment to `_28_` is mistaken: it should  be `2` but it is `0`. I compared with Icarus, which gives the correct response.

![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/737be6e6-d6bc-4cf9-89e4-f9a81b4b907c)

`top.v`
```
